#MealPrepping is ideal for those trying to manage what they eat. It’s not always easy deciding what to eat for the day while also making sure you get your needed #nutrients. A sure way to tackle both of those issues is meal prepping. Meal prepping allows you to eat healthier, manage your #weight, and save time and money. Somebody once told me “I don’t have enough time for meal prepping”. Yes, time can often hinder us from eating a healthy diet, in fact recent studies show that there is a link between poor eating habits and time (see study here). However, if you spend two hours preparing food for the rest of the week you can actually save time as well as know exactly what you’re putting into your body. #PortionControl is one of the factors in #weightloss and through meal prepping you can manage and prioritize your meals for that week. To quote Adam Drewnowski, director of the UW’s Center for Public Health Nutrition “By cooking more often at home, you have a better diet at no significant cost increase, while if you go out more, you have a less healthy diet at a higher cost." This meal prep photo includes #vegan meals that i’ve prepared on DivineInHerKitchen.com. Since this prep is #nutrition based it isn’t ideal for those trying to loose #weight because it is 2000 #calories. You can take out the lunch and snack for a little over 1,000 calories and burn 100-200 just by daily activities. It’s a flexible meal prep that includes key nutrients.

Breakfast: #Avocado on wheat toast w/ hemp seed (Recipe Here)

Multivitamin drink: #GreenSuperfood Pineapple Lemongrass really tasty if you add a little lemon juice and agave!

#PostWorkout: Spinach, banana, dole frozen mixed fruit, raw vanilla plant protein, flax milk with protein, almonds. 
#BCAA: Xtend BCAAs while working out to help support muscle growth & strength.

@hashi88  I have always been overweight since childhood. Even through high school I struggled with my weight and had self image issues. During my first year of university I tried to change my eating habits to lose weight but had less or no motivation at all. With the stresses of university I ate really bad and continued to struggle with my weight. 
I have always wanted to dress nicely and have the curves to show off, but because of my overweight body it seemed a dream.
Then one day a friend upload a group photo with me in it on Facebook , and I got really bad comments on my figure and how overweight I was. I was devastated and had a emotional breakdown. After that I decided to fully commit to losing the weight, so started eating healthy and going to the gym 6 days a week. After 10 months of fully committed to the diet and training, I lost 42 kgs. This change in my body further motivated me to keep going. I started to dress nicely and loved to show my new curves. This added further to my motivation.
I trained harder and became stronger and fitter. My ultimate motivation  is the results I see within myself and that itself is my inspiration.
